            // Module: Art as Investment
            Module(
                id: "mod_art",
                title: "Art as Investment",
                description: "Understanding Art Markets and Alternative Assets. Explore the economics of art, auction dynamics, and how art functions as an investment vehicle.",
                icon: "🎨",
                color: "blue",
                heroImageName: "hero_art",
                sections: [
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_art_1",
                        title: "1. Alternative Investing in Art_",
                        content: [
                            .text("Alternative investments now make up a larger share of portfolios held by institutional investors compared to just a few years ago. (1) Our goal here is to dive into investing in Art as a tangible asset. This module will open up a distinct alternative investing option, provide detailed information within the space and allow for investor confidence to grow in the alternative space as well.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_art_2",
                        title: "Let this be a love letter to art, in economic terms…",
                        content: [
                            .heading("🕸️ 1.1 Inside the Seemingly Opaque Industry_", level: 3),
                            .text("The Art Market. The term itself can feel daunting from the outside. "),
                            .text("First, one must understand that the art market has a variety of factors at play. The term “art market” is viewed as a monolithic category. In reality a convening subset of unique players actually dictate the market itself. This risk is as is with other forms of investment. On whole, similar to the world of Private Equity there are not as many vehicles of transparency to the process, which is why on the outside it can look to many as an unattainable asset class. "),
                            .text("Each submarket is defined by artists and genres. The global art market is comprised of a network of auction houses, dealers, galleries, advisors, agents, individual collectors, museums, public institutions, and various experts and service providers engaged in the purchase and sale of unique and collectible works of art. "),
                            .heading("☎️ 1.2 By the Numbers_", level: 3),
                            .text("According to the 2023 UBS Art Market Report, the global art market maintained steady growth in the face of profound unpredictability underscores the robustness of the post-pandemic art market. Global art sales in 2022 recorded a 3% year-on-year increase, reaching an estimated total of $67.8 billion. This surpassed the pre-pandemic levels observed in 2019. However, it's important to note that not all segments of the market experienced uniform gains. (2)"),
                            .text("All of this was in-spite of significant economic uncertainty and the return of conflict to Europe, the art market continued to build on its post-pandemic recovery and even strengthened further. While financial markets experienced declines due to central banks' efforts to combat inflation and unsettling images of destruction on television screens, collectors remained steadfast in their commitment to the art market. All indicating a cautious yet resilient growth amidst the uncertainty."),
                            .text("Previous to global upheaval, the 2020 Art Basel Report, global art sales were $64.1 billion in 2019, down 5% year-over-year from 2018. The same report estimates that global sales have remained between $57 billion and $68 billion over the past decade, except during 2009 when sales declined to approximately $40 billion which is believed to have been caused by the global financial crisis. From 2009 to 2019, global art sales have grown at a 5.0% CAGR. (3)"),
                            .text("From 2020 to 2022 the market actually grew in the middle of a world wide pandemic, the invasion of Ukraine and Russian sanctions, among many other economic factors during this time. "),
                            .text("In 2019, auction sales by Sotheby’s, Christie’s and Phillips totaled $9.7 billion, down 20% from 2018, according to the 2019 ArtTactic Auction Review. Adjusted for the sale of the Peggy and David Rockefeller Collection held at Christie’s in May 2018 and the sale of the Barney A. Ebsworth Collection held at Christie’s in November 2018, auction sales by these houses were down 12% from 2018. Post-War and Contemporary art auction market sales volume rose 4.6% to $4.1 billion in 2019 from 2018."),
                            .text("In 2020, the economic disruption resulting from the COVID-19 pandemic significantly impacted the schedule of public auction sales for the first half of 2020. Consequently, auction sales volume by Sotheby’s, Christie’s and Phillips totaled $2.9 billion or a 49% decrease in the first half of 2020 compared to the same period in 2019 according to the First Half 2020 ArtTactic Auction Review. (4)  Post-War and Contemporary art auction market sales volume fared better than the overall market, falling by 34% to $1.5 billion in the first half of 2020 versus the same period in 2019. However, the economic disruption led to significant growth in online-only sales, which increased nearly six fold in the first half of 2020 versus the same period in 2019. In late June and early July 2020, the auction market for high-end artwork resumed in earnest when Christie’s, Sotheby’s and Phillips combined their previously postponed evening sales into hybrid evening sales selling a total of $709.2 million or 14% above the total pre-sale low estimate and selling 95% of all lots."),
                            .text("The global art market is influenced over time by the overall strength and stability of the global economy, geopolitical conditions, capital markets and world events, all of which may affect the willingness of potential buyers and sellers to purchase and sell art. While the global art market is large, its exact size is unknown and statistical data is inconsistent. Much of the uncertainty stems from differing estimates of the size of the private dealer and gallery market, which is based on survey data, but disparities also exist in reported auction sales."),
                            .callout(title: "Investment Note", content: "Typically paintings carry more significance for investment purposes than drawings and/or sculptures. ", type: .info),
                            .heading("🧭 1.3 Play the \"Long Game\"", level: 3),
                            .text("A well constructed portfolio answers several questions, mainly around your personal risk tolerance. Even the best wealth advisor, hedge fund managers and private equity investors have losses. A successful career built on a personal assessment of their risk comfort. The investments that do fail show the investor when and how they navigate their personal emotions of the market. The trick is to survive those down turns and have a diversified enough portfolio to hedge against major losses. "),
                            .text("Assessing volatility and economic risk is essential in evaluating any investment, and to be straight forward, there is a specific lack of transparency within the art market and art investing, so with caution and eyes wide open, look at those risks along with the benefits. Economic risk pertains to the inherent, unaltered risk associated with these investments. It's crucial for investors to consider both of these aspects."),
                            .text("The primary motivation for considering alternative investments lies in their potential to enhance the risk-to-reward ratio for investors, not only from an appraised standpoint but also from an economic perspective. Looking ahead, we anticipate that they typical returns of non-alternative investments will likely be lower compared to historical averages. This trend is applicable to public markets as well, especially in fixed income investments. However, the advantage of diversification will persist, and we anticipate ongoing developments and innovations in the investment landscape."),
                            .text("One significant challenge for many investors is the practical implementation of alternative investments. They demand more oversight and management compared to investments in public markets. The search and due diligence expenses are substantial due to the closed-end or private nature of many of these investment opportunities. Creating and maintaining portfolios of this nature necessitates experienced teams or involves significant outsourcing costs. (5)"),
                            .text("The primary principle underpinning portfolio management is effective diversification. This involves identifying and combining assets that exhibit low correlations with each other, thereby achieving a portfolio risk level lower than that of the individual assets considered in isolation. Art has demonstrated consistently low and even negative correlations with many other asset classes over various time frames, making it an attractive option for diversification. This diversification advantage extends not only to portfolios that blend diverse assets with art but also within a single art collection. By strategically combining different categories of art, one can effectively hedge against risk."),
                            .divider
                        ],
