                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_art_3",
                        title: "2. For the Love of Investing_",
                        content: [
                            .callout(title: "Emotional Premium", content: "How one arrives at the premium varies depending on the artwork, artist, time of sale and the buyer itself. There are very real moments within the art world where purchases are made well beyond the seemingly reasonable valuation of an artwork. This concept is known as an 'emotional premium.'", type: .keyPoint),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .heading("💥 2.1 Emotions_", level: 3),
                            .text("Once such a record price is paid, particularly when it carries a high emotional premium, the likelihood of finding another buyer in the short or medium term with both a similar emotional connection to the piece and the financial means to purchase it becomes exceedingly slim. This holds true even if the work were to return to the market at the same price, let alone attempting to profit from its resale. In essence, despite the extensive media attention they garner, record-breaking artworks like this often turn out to be less than ideal financial investments, primarily due to the challenges associated with reselling them, given the strong emotional attachment they carry."),
                            .heading("🧨 2.2 The Look of ‘Dr. Gachet’_", level: 3),
                            .text("Well documented and the groundbreaking sale of van Gogh's Portrait of Dr. Gachet at Christie's New York in 1990 broke all records the time. The work itself fetched $82.5 million. This masterpiece found its new owner in the affluent Japanese paper-industry magnate, Ryoei Saito. During the New York auction, Saito's representative aggressively bid, following Saito's directive to secure the painting at any cost. As described in the New York Times, Mr. Saito had seen the work “two years ago at the Metropolitan Museum of Art and ‘fell in love with it.’'’ (6) Saito's motivation was deeply personal, as he claimed that the melancholic portrayal of Dr. Gachet resonated with his own emotions. "),
                            .text("Regardless of his motivations, it's evident that a substantial emotional component significantly influenced the final winning bid for the artwork. Saito's intention was to hold onto the painting for the long term, rather than seeking a quick profit through resale."),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .artworkCard(artist: "Vincent van Gogh", title: "Portrait of Dr. Gachet", year: "1890", salePrice: "$82.5 million", auctionHouse: "Christie's, New York", saleDate: "1990"),
                            .spacer(height: .medium),
                            .heading("😅 2.3 NFT and Beeple_", level: 3),
                            .text("Everydays — The First 5000 Days, is an NFT (non fungible token) aka, a digital JPEG file sold in its first every auction at Christies for $69 million. The artist previously unknown to anyone outside the very specific crypto world was just as shocked by the purchase price as well. Only diving into the crypto space six months earlier, the artist who has been in digital production for over a decade, found the ability to use smart contracts for ownership intriguing. (7)"),
                            .text("With seconds counting down, the lot was set to sell for under $30 million, but a flurry of last-minute bids promoted an extension of the auction to push the final price over the $60 million mark. According to Rebecca Riegelhaupt, a Christie’s spokeswoman, the result of the 33 active bidders contesting the work made it third highest auction price achieved for a living artist, only after Jeff Koons and David Hockney. "),
                            .text("The digital artwork is a culmination and collage of multiple artworks done over the course of 5000 days or a bit over fourteen years. This fact alone is what intrigued the collector the most. "),
                            .text("The collector, Vignesh Sundaresan, aka MetaKovan to the cryptocurrency community spoke on his purchase of this historic sale. What he found most intriguing about the work was its representation of time. Essentially, you cannot purchase time, but through this work, he managed to do so. Sundaresan shared with Bloomberg that his intention was both to highlight the technology and to show support for the artist. (8)"),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .artworkCard(artist: "Beeple (Mike Winkelmann)", title: "Everydays: The First 5000 Days", year: "2021", salePrice: "$69.3 million", auctionHouse: "Christie's", saleDate: "March 11, 2021"),
                            .spacer(height: .medium),
                            .heading("🍇 2.4 ‘Salvator Mundi’ by Leonardo da Vinci", level: 3),
                            .text("Who knew a seemingly simple depiction of medieval Jesus Christ, painted around 1500, would become the single most expensive painting to date. "),
                            .text("Painted at the request of King Louis XII of France, lost and forgotten for centuries until it was discovered at a New Orleans estate sale, touted as a “lost” Leonardo da Vinci. (9)"),
                            .text("In the span of 18 short and incredibly dramatic minutes, the Salvator Mundi sold at Christies in 2017 for $450.3m with fees. More than four times its estimate of $100m. Until then, no artwork had sold for more than $200m at auction. (10)"),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .artworkCard(artist: "Leonardo da Vinci", title: "Salvator Mundi", year: "c. 1490–1519", salePrice: "$450.3 million", auctionHouse: "Christie's, New York", saleDate: "2017"),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .text("Previously in 2011 the work was restored and exhibited at the National Portrait Gallery in London. The work itself changed hands until the Russian Oligarch, Dmitry E. Rybolovlev, put it up for auction. "),
                            .text("The work, over the course of the years has brought controversy, including its origin."),
                            .text("Now seemingly owned by Bader bin Abdullah bin Mohammed bin Farhan al-Saud, was the elusive bidder who purchased the work at the astounding price. Even the optics of a prince from the royal family of a Muslim country to purchase a painting of Christ as set off flags. (11)"),
                            .text("The art world was then ablaze the work was planned to be displayed at the anniversary show of the Louvre. Secretly shipped by the crown prince to the Louvre, in 2018, it never made it to the curated show. Essentially caught up in customs, it actually belongs to the Saudi Cultural Ministry. "),
                            .text("To this day, the Salvator Mundi is the only da Vinci in private hands."),
                            .heading("🐇 2.5 ‘Love Is in the Bin’ repurposed by Banksy_ ", level: 3),
                            .text("Originally titled Girl With Balloon, created by Bansky, found itself to be a conceptual art piece during its 2018 sale at auction. After the hammer hit to confirm the Sotheby’s sale for $1.4 million, an alarm could be heard. The artwork itself started to shred. Inside the frame a hidden device was installed to shred the painting until it jammed at the halfway mark.  "),
                            .text("Secured partially, the new owner of the work, along with everyone in the London auction room, found the surprise destruction all part of the Banksy process. "),
                            .text("According to the statement made by Sotheby’s the next day, (12) the woman who purchased the artwork found its value held despite the self-destruction. Speculation that the work became more valuable after the artist created the memorable moment, as well as be hailed as a ““masterpiece of radical performance,”(13) proved out at an auction a few short years later. "),
                            .spacer(height: .small),
                            .table(
                                headers: ["Year", "Title", "Sale Price", "Auction House"],
                                rows: [
                                    ["2018", "Girl With Balloon", "$1.4 million", "Sotheby's London"],
                                    ["2021", "Love is in the Bin", "$25.4 million", "Sotheby's"]
                                ],
                                caption: "The Banksy work's dramatic value increase after self-destruction"
                            ),
                            .divider
                        ],
