            // BONUS Sub-Module: Kahlo x Basquiat (nested within Art as Investment)
            Module(
                id: "mod_kahlo_basquiat",
                title: "Bonus: Kahlo x Basquiat",
                description: "Accidental Bedfellows - exploring two of the world's greatest artists through the lens of trauma, healing, and artistic expression.",
                icon: "🎭",
                color: "coral",
                heroImageName: "hero_kahlo_basquiat",
                sections: [
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_1",
                        title: "Introduction",
                        content: [
                            .text("This module will cover a fundamental component of two of the world's greatest artists: Frida Kahlo and Jean-Michel Basquiat.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_2",
                        title: "Shared Stories_",
                        content: [
                            .text("Artists Frida Kahlo and Jean Michel Basquiat sought to understand truth. In the discovery of their worlds within and the interplay of outer events catalyzed some of the greatest modern art ever."),
                            .text("While generations apart, each were involved in accidents that left them hospitalized. Bones shattered. These separate experiences were conveyed heavily in each bodies of artwork. This short module explores two specific works: Kahlo's La Columna Rota (The Broken Column), 1944 and Basquiat's The Anatomy Series."),
                            .heading("Cataclysmic Events_", level: 3),
                            .text("For both, these events return to the automobile. An everyday mode of transportation that altered the fates of each. Both Kahlo and Basquiat used their art as a tool. Each in their own passion sought to find meaning, explanation, hope and honesty from a singular event. Each childhood moment would become the Zero Point of their foundations as artists as well as two beings living a very human experience."),
                            .text("Kahlo notably was not shy about her body. From every scar to every significant life event, her artwork consistently depicted the mapping of each trauma. Here we will focus on her work Self Portrait, The Broken Column."),
                            .text("It is a work that resonates with Basquiat's Human Anatomy drawings. Viewing the series of drawings from earlier in his career a direct correlation is made to the history of his other works."),
                            .text("For Kahlo and Basquiat, we the viewers can learn a great deal in the reflections of their life events. Basquiat fascination with x-rays, bones and the human anatomy mirrors Kahlo's expression of her own breaking and healing and breaking.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_3",
                        title: "Mind, Body, Art_ Observations of the Human Form",
                        content: [
                            .quote("Be Alive for this time.", author: nil),
                            .text("Frida Kahlo and Jean-Michel Basquiat works dive deep into the Life/Death/Life cycle. Both portrayed the broken, human form."),
                            .divider,
                            .text("Artists endeavor to use all forms of visual communications. Typically they will utilize accessible technology of their day. Technology in conjunction with the human form, a bridge from the old world to the new. Each waged an artistic declaration of inequities and inequalities using their culturally relevant language. To know love of oneself and to know connection was their Modus Operandi of choice reflected in works produced. Both artists sought to change our way of seeing. Both excelled and succeeded at the venture.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_4",
                        title: "1. Frida Kahlo_",
                        content: [
                            .text("On the afternoon of September 17, 1925, Kahlo and her high-school boyfriend, Alejandro Arias, were riding from downtown Mexico City when a vehicle collided with the trolley car they were occupying. Arias escaped with only minor injuries, but he witnessed Kahlo gravely injured. The brut force of the accident stripped Kahlo of her clothing. At first glance, there was an iron trolley handrail that impaled her through her pelvis. Arias along with the help of others, removed the handrail, causing immediate and immense pain. Screams ripped through the San Juan market. (1)"),
                            .text("She also broke her spine in three places, right leg in eleven, her shoulder was dislocated, her collarbone broken and spinal column severely injured. Her crushed right leg and broken right foot also required attention. The trolley iron handrail pierced her abdomen and her uterus. (2,3)"),
                            .text("During her month-long hospital recovery she took up painting. Her mother concocted a specially-made lap easel that allowed her to paint from bed. She included a mirror about her bed for self-portraits."),
                            .text("The accident changed everything. Kahlo's entire world shifted. According to her she gained knowledge few encounter- like lightning elucidating the earth. Determined to not be slowed down both physically and emotionally she insisted on practicing movements. Despite the intense and agonizing pain."),
                            .text("Unable to initially walk, she worked for months to improve her condition. That type of perseverance and fortitude would prove to be a familiar muscle in the future."),
                            .text("It made her a force to be reckoned with as a young woman in a cultural setting that had few options for women. This allowed her to explore more complex issues, especially in the Surrealist Movement.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_5",
                        title: "1.2 Medical Moments_",
                        content: [
                            .text("After her accident she took up painting as part of her recovery. Being well versed since childhood with continuous visits with doctors and specialists, her understanding of human anatomy and truly her own body guided her subsequent interests. Her artistic body of work."),
                            .text("Having wanted to go into medicine, Kahlo was fascinated with medical imagery. It was a point of reference and inspiration. She was incredibly fascinated with the human form."),
                            .text("She and her husband, the artist Diego Rivera were enthralled with medical books. Her detailed knowledge of the human organism brings life to her artwork. Their close circle of friends included those from a more scientific background. Horticulturists, doctors and industrialists graced their dinner table. (6) Her time in the US exemplified this love. (6.1) Her work increasingly became more anatomically expressive.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_6",
                        title: "Self Portrait, The Broken Column_",
                        content: [
                            .heading("The Body_", level: 3),
                            .text("In discussing Kahlo's accident, Lomas and Howell wrote that her \"resulting scars were deeply etched.\" They examine her painting The Broken Column, 1944, which they say references \"that first trauma.\" (4)"),
                            .text("The first thing you see when looking upon this work is her face. Her gaze with so much expression, so much anguish, looks straight at you. Depending on how you have navigated your own life, you may feel incredibly uncomfortable with her directness. Or you it may resonate. Her gaze has the ability to track. To leave nothing and no one unnoticed."),
                            .text("Highly steeped in religious symbolism, Kahlo's knowledge of the Catholic faith could lead one to concluded her symbiotic use of nails. With her knowledge of the life and teachings of Jesus, along with the Catholic teachings of the New Testament, the tears and sweat coming down her face, is similar to the story of Jesus sweating blood in the Garden of Gethsemane. (8)"),
                            .text("To be in such physical pain the literal use of nails will also depict to the viewer a representation of the internal. Inner turmoil is rarely seen. Kahlo has a gift of portraying the internal. What is significant is her use of truth provides essential data. The entire body succumbs."),
                            .text("Aztec ruins were much of an inspiration in Kahlo's work. If you look closely enough, notice the metal structure that replaces her spine resembles an Aztec structure. Since her accident caused three vertebrae to be permanently out of place and with an infinity for mysticism and alchemy, Kahlo utilizes clear symbolism within her spinal column. A literal column (look at the axis point for the C3-C5) she continues to play with the materials of old and industrial. In part it also has the feeling of a Roman column."),
                            .heading("The Land_", level: 3),
                            .text("An interesting observation of this particular painting is in part the background. Relative to her other works, it is comparatively sparse. The subtle layers of broken land mimic the broken bones. In desolation and despair Kahlo captures the true nature of the human spirit in times of extreme. One could point to similarity of the Mona Lisa. Her love of Leonardo DaVinci and his work was apparent soon after her accident. She went through a rebirth. So much so she made a birth announcement of a baby named Leonardo. (6.1)"),
                            .text("Skies less complex in composition but just as telling. Movement of storms. The emotions of a teenage girl encapsulated in a grown woman remind us that tragedy is never far off, but neither is self-enlightenment."),
                            .callout(title: "🌟 Reflection", content: "Think of a time in your life or in the environment that reflects broken systems. How can you best utilize those moments? For yourself, for others? In the context of the financial system, do you see potential of a transformation that includes our current global \"vibe-cession\"?", type: .tip)
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_7",
                        title: "2. Basquiat_",
                        content: [
                            .text("Basquiat's work is ubiquitous with our time. While he is no longer alive, a presence in the 70's and 80's, his legacy stretches deeply today. Some of his earlier pieces, The Anatomy Series (1982), we will be examining here. Incredibly prolific, but not quite as well known, this series help set the stage for his later work."),
                            .heading("2.1 Anatomy", level: 3),
                            .text("Bones, the drawing of our basic anatomical building blocks. Basquiat examines the human fundamentals in the most distilled format. Replications of X-Rays produced a reflective quality."),
                            .text("This series made during an energy inducing creative spree, helped propel Basquiat into critical success. In 1981, painting on found doors and windows while making a home wherever he could find a spare couch, Basquiat worked tirelessly. By 1982, the year this series was created, Basquiat became an overnight critical success. He had several shows in New York, Los Angeles and Europe. Having found a loft of Crosby Street in SoHo, Basquiat went to town on artistically exploring every part of his psyche."),
                            .text("Known to produce in groupings, The Anatomy Series, consists of a grouping of singular bone structures with the look of negatives and the feel of a medical textbook. Later making a name for himself by replicating images from history, fashion and culture- the distillation point for much personal exploration, was the Gray's Anatomy textbook."),
                            .text("The significance of multiples allows puts a dynamic stake in the ground. Since his entire body was involved in the accident, not one area was left unscrutinized. His life was his art. Directly and more than most artists. He left no stone unturned, nor life event not fully covered. This transparency translates in black and white."),
                            .text("For example, this work featuring the right clavicle- both front and upper view. For a clavicle injury to heal, it takes great time and is incredibly painful."),
                            .text("Is Basquiat showcasing his particular physical trauma through this seemingly simple work?"),
                            .text("Yes.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_8",
                        title: "Basquiat's Origins_",
                        content: [
                            .text("Basquiat's fascination of art started in early childhood. His mother Matilda, regularly took him to the Brooklyn Museum, not far from their Park Slope family home. Venturing into the city to visit the Metropolitan Museum of Art and Museum of Modern Art, captured the young artists imagination. According to his father, Gerald, Basquiat started drawing around age four."),
                            .text("While playing ball, Basquiat at the age of seven, was hit by a car. During his month long hospitalization, Matilde gave him a copy of the famed Gray's Anatomy textbook. From this accident he suffered a broken arm, various internal injuries as well as had to have his spleen removed. Such injuries resulted in a treacherous healing process. This event had a profound impact on Basquiat that we see continue throughout his art career. (10)"),
                            .text("Significantly, if not prolifically, in the series The Anatomy Series, Basquiat seemingly replicates the feeling of X-Rays. On black using white grease crayon, he builds out emotion surrounding the broken body- both from the patient and physician's perspective."),
                            .text("For Basquiat to do an entire series in the Basquiat way, he points to the larger themes of his other works. The patient, on some level, is always powerless. He/She is in the hands of another. This is a direct observation of power, pain and futility that is central to his overall body of work."),
                            .text("Combining the anatomical drawings with the skill of Egyptian hieroglyphics, these works bear witness to his celebrated skills of a formation of a well researched, multi-cultural aesthetic."),
                            .text("Observe the stark drawings of bones, joints and skull profile. The renditions are brute, honest and primal. Think of drawings of early man on cave walls. Knowing his later work- speaking truth in complex times with daunting complex social injustices, it is safe to point to the truth Basquiat is stating: that we are each a make-up of flesh and bone."),
                            .text("Though not explicitly applied in this series, the background of racial injustices, especially care for the African American community within the medical field is implicitly implied. Most of his other bodies of work address the hypocrisy of living and being in one of the most influential cities in the world yet not having equal access to any resource."),
                            .text("His work was critical of the institutional racism prevalent in the 1980's, both in the contemporary art world and the United States as a whole.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_9",
                        title: "Basquiat's Legacy_",
                        content: [
                            .text("Known for his extensive reading of history, science and culture, Basquiat distills down complex issues in a child-like way. In Anatomy Basquiat points to the very building blocks of our body. His lifelong work was to convey the very building blocks of our society. This is the starting point- our own anatomy."),
                            .divider,
                            .text("Over the span of Basquiat's short career, he captured the essence of a specific time, place and purpose. We will cover more of his works and themes in an upcoming module, but what is important to realize is his profound impact on the art world, as well as how these anatomical artworks speak of more than meets the eye."),
                            .text("Known for his array of multiple sources of inspiration, Basquiat moves from dominating esoteric ideologies and topics. He had extreme interest in other artists works, mainly Leonardo da Vinci's anatomical drawings to Pablo Picasso Cubist figures. His own Haitian heritage and life in Brooklyn mixed with to musical inclinations of jazz. Multiple themes live within his works. Throughout however is the deep emotional landscape, either reflected in choice of subject, iconography, or messaging. Basquiat had a unique ability to touch upon the psychological underworld within himself as well as society around him."),
                            .text("If you look closely, some works are signed by SAMO. The origin of SAMO dates back to his days on the Lower East Side of Manhattan of graffiti and street art. Under this pseudonym graffiti turned to poetry. (13, 14) By virtue of his poetry he taught and unleashed a philosophers point of view through the lens of tangible art."),
                            .text("Tangibility is a noteworthy theme in all of Basquiat's work. The viewer can grasp his images as their own. One can look and immediately relate. An image of a bone, a building or bird, Basquiat drew of subjects not of one specific time and place, rather universal objects one may point to directly in their own psyche."),
                            .text("His later works from his time in LA, under the show Heroes and Monsters: The Thaddeus Mumford Jr. Venice Collection address the more complex psychological nature of his accident. But to begin with- the simplicity of bones is the base of his early genius."),
                            .text("In order to understand this collection, one must side step the initial criticism. One must lean into the foundational points of these works."),
                            .text("Basquiat did pursue not only his dream, but the core of his world view.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    ),
                    Section(
                        id: "sec_mod_kb_10",
                        title: "Conclusion: Universal Healing_",
                        content: [
                            .callout(title: "🌒 Consider", content: "Consider the overarching social and financial implications of these works", type: .tip),
                            .text("While Frida Kahlo and Jean-Michel Basquiat were generations apart their works featuring their own healing processes are universal. Both had the profound ability to allow the viewer to see themselves in the art works they are observing. While you may have not been in such extreme car accidents, you most likely have either been in a health scare or for women, navigated the complexities of fertility Kahlo explores."),
                            .text("The importance of both Basquiat and Kahlo in the context of our cultural understanding and identities is vast. From the perspective of investing- art is a unique language that transcends time. How important is it not to support poignant works that shape our identities?"),
                            .text("What makes this section unique is from a forward thinking moment. For purely investing purposes, when considering an emerging artist, can you consider how their works play into the global, human narrative?"),
                            .text("Another point that is obvious, but rarely discussed, is both of these artists are minorities. In the Blue-Chip art world, most works recognized are from artists of a specific gender and race. It is important to note how both Kahlo and Basquiat transcended incredible obstacles."),
                            .text("Each are able to span complexities of race, gender, nationality and socio-economic disparities while authentically representing their own heritage, frailties and language. They offer an invisible hand of peace."),
                            .text("In a time and place where art is needed more than ever before, our goal is to bring our investors the absolute best options within the naturally opaque Blue-Chip art market. Our hope is with this quick module you will be able to consider how you want to navigate investing in artwork as well as how previous collectors have been drawn to certain artists, cultural significance, and financial value.")
                        ],
                        isCollapsible: true,
                        level: 2,
                        reflectionPrompts: [],
                        glossaryTerms: [],
                        relatedResearch: []
                    )
                ],
